{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1314"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1314"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.47,0.04,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92380"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1314"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75685"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31540"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92380"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 47-year-old woman attends the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of severe, colicky left loin pain, which radiates down into her groin. It is unrelieved by paracetamol, which she has taken at home. In between episodes of pain she looks well, with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 125/85 mmHg, temperature 37.4C, and a soft abdomen. Urinalysis shows traces of blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA non-contrast CT scan shows a 5 mm stone in her distal left ureter. There are no other significant findings on CT.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tamsulosin","Ibuprofen","Nifedipine","Ureteroscopy","Extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stone can be expected to pass spontaneously. Management should start with pain control and a \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-steroidal anti-inflammatory agent\u003C/strong\u003E (such as ibuprofen) would be most appropriate. Whilst most patients who present to an emergency department with symptoms consistent with ureteric colic will have some form of imaging (usually at CT urogram), the large majority will not require any form of active intervention. In a study from the United States, the profile of over 55,000 patients who presented to emergency departments with renal colic symptoms was analysed and whilst 77% had CT imaging, only 9% required hospitalisation, with most patients being discharged directly from the emergency department. Of all the patients, only 9% required some form of urological intervention within the first week and 17% with the first two months. In other words, most patients with renal tract stones who present with renal colic will pass their stone spontaneously and can be managed on an out-patient basis. Any need for immediate investigation in the Emergency Department will probably be unnecessary for most of these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most ureteric stones \u003C5 mm will pass spontaneously, and 50% 5-7mm will pass spontaneously"],"references":["Schoenfeld EM, Shieh M-S, Pekow PS, et al. Association of Patient and Visit Characteristics With Rate and Timing of Urologic Procedures for Patients Discharged From the Emergency Department With Renal Colic. JAMA Network Open. 2019;2(12):e1916454"]},"relati